<header class="hero">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="eyebrow">The playbook</div>
    <h1>Your building is expiring.<br>Here's what to <span>actually do</span>.</h1>
    <p class="deck">
      Written by a tenant who has done every one of these things — some of them badly, some of
      them too late. This is not legal advice. It's the thing I wish someone had handed me
      the day we found out.
    </p>
  </div>
</header>

<main class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">

    <div class="note">
      <b>Read this part first, before anything else.</b>
      <strong>An expiring tax credit is not an eviction notice.</strong> It does not mean you have to
      leave. It does not mean your rent goes up tomorrow. In many buildings, other protections
      survive the expiration — Good Cause Eviction, a rent-stabilization overlay from a different
      tax benefit, SCRIE or DRIE if you're a senior or disabled. In my own building, our lawyers
      argued that most units remained protected even after the credit ran out.
      <br><br>
      You are not out of time. You are out of <em>warning</em>. Those are different, and the
      difference is everything you're about to do.
    </div>

    <h2 style="margin-top:48px">The eight things</h2>

    <div class="steps">

      <div class="step">
        <h3>Organize. Before anything else, and before you feel ready.</h3>
        <p>
          Everything else on this list is downstream of this one. A single tenant asking a landlord
          questions gets nowhere. Seventy tenants asking together is a different building.
        </p>
        <p>
          If we had not organized, I do not believe we would still be here. That is not a slogan.
          It is the plain assessment of what happened.
        </p>
        <p>
          Form a tenants association. Knock on doors. Start with the neighbors you already talk to.
          You do not need everyone — you need enough to make the first meeting real.
        </p>
        <p style="margin-top:14px">
          <a href="/resources/" style="color:var(--navy);font-weight:700">Find a tenant union in your borough →</a>
        </p>
        <div class="call">
          <strong>Legal Aid — Housing Justice Unit, Group Advocacy</strong>
          <span>
            This helpline exists specifically to help tenants start and run a tenants association.
            <a href="tel:2125777988">212-577-7988</a>, Monday–Friday 10am–4pm.
          </span>
        </div>
        <span class="now">Do this first</span>
      </div>

      <div class="step">
        <h3>Find out when your building expires — and don't assume the answer is knowable.</h3>
        <p>
          Look your building up in the registry. But understand what you're getting: a
          <strong>projection</strong>, not a filed date. The federal database estimates it by adding
          thirty years to the year the building opened, because in many cases there is nothing
          better to go on.
        </p>
        <p>
          In my building, the attorneys on both sides disagreed on the date. The landlord's counsel
          wasn't sure. It ended up being <em>negotiated</em>. If your date turns out to be
          contested, you are not being paranoid and you are not alone.
        </p>
        <div class="call">
          <strong>Ask, in writing, and keep the answer</strong>
          <span>
            Ask your landlord and your state housing agency for the regulatory agreement and the
            expiration date, in writing. Whatever comes back — including nothing — is useful later.
          </span>
        </div>
        <p style="margin-top:14px">
          <a href="/find-your-building/" style="color:var(--navy);font-weight:700">Search the registry →</a>
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="step">
        <h3>Get free legal help. You almost certainly qualify.</h3>
        <p>
          Do not wait for a court case. The best time to have a lawyer is <em>before</em> anything
          is filed, when there's still room to act.
        </p>
        <div class="call">
          <strong>Met Council on Housing — Tenants' Rights Hotline</strong>
          <span><a href="tel:2129790611">212-979-0611</a>. Volunteer counselors, not lawyers, but among the most knowledgeable people on tenant rights in this city. Start here if you're unsure who to call.</span>
        </div>
        <div class="call">
          <strong>Right to Counsel / Eviction Free NYC</strong>
          <span><a href="tel:7185571379">718-557-1379</a> or <a href="https://www.evictionfreenyc.org" target="_blank" rel="noopener">evictionfreenyc.org</a>. Free representation in Housing Court, in every ZIP code, regardless of immigration status.</span>
        </div>
        <div class="call">
          <strong>Housing Court Answers</strong>
          <span><a href="tel:2129624795">212-962-4795</a>, Tuesday–Thursday, 9am–5pm.</span>
        </div>
        <div class="call">
          <strong>Legal Aid Society</strong>
          <span>Brooklyn 718-722-3100 · Manhattan 212-426-3000 · Bronx 718-991-4600 · Queens 718-286-2450 · Staten Island 347-422-5333</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="step">
        <h3>Find a preservation buyer — early, and on your terms.</h3>
        <p>
          There are nonprofit affordable housing organizations whose entire purpose is buying
          buildings like yours and keeping them affordable. If your landlord is going to sell,
          the question is not <em>whether</em> the building sells. It's <em>to whom</em>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Start looking before there's a buyer, not after. A nonprofit needs time to do due
          diligence, get an appraisal, and assemble public financing. If you wait until the
          "For Sale" sign goes up, you have already lost the race.
        </p>
        <p>
          And be prepared for the landlord to obstruct this. Ours refused to give our nonprofit
          partner the access it needed to complete an appraisal — which the city and state
          require. That obstruction is a tactic. Document it.
        </p>
        <div class="call">
          <strong>UHAB — the people who actually do this</strong>
          <span>
            The Urban Homesteading Assistance Board has taken roughly 1,600 buildings from
            distressed rental into resident-owned affordable co-ops since 1973, with a reported
            99% success rate. They will come to your building and walk you through it.
            <a href="tel:2124793333">212-479-3333</a> · <a href="https://www.uhab.org" target="_blank" rel="noopener">uhab.org</a>
          </span>
        </div>
        <div class="call">
          <strong>The strongest version of this: community ownership</strong>
          <span>
            A community land trust takes the building off the speculative market permanently —
            no thirty-year clock, because there's no clock at all. Start with
            <a href="https://www.neweconomyproject.org" target="_blank" rel="noopener">New Economy Project</a>
            (<a href="mailto:info@neweconomyproject.org">info@neweconomyproject.org</a>), who convene
            the city's CLT alliance and give one-on-one support to tenants trying this.
            <a href="/community-ownership/">Read how it works →</a>
          </span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="step">
        <h3>Go public, and go loud.</h3>
        <p>
          A landlord's greatest asset is that nobody is watching. Take that away.
        </p>
        <p>
          Rally in front of the building. Call the press — City Limits, the local papers, the
          neighborhood blogs. Make a website. Make a hashtag. Get your council member, your
          Assembly member, your state senator, the borough president, the comptroller, the public
          advocate on the record in writing.
        </p>
        <p>
          Our goal from day one was that everyone in this city would know what was happening at
          63 Tiffany Place. That visibility is the reason we still have a building to fight for.
        </p>
        <div class="call">
          <strong>See how we did it</strong>
          <span>
            Every rally, every letter, every piece of press —
            <a href="https://save63tiffany.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener">save63tiffany.com</a>.
            Steal all of it.
          </span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="step">
        <h3>Document everything. Starting today.</h3>
        <p>
          Every letter. Every notice. Every conversation, written down the same day with the date
          on it. Every repair request and every non-response. Every rent increase. Photograph the
          conditions.
        </p>
        <p>
          You will not know which of these matters until a lawyer asks you for it, and by then it
          is too late to start.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="step">
        <h3>Expect retaliation. It is illegal, and it happens anyway.</h3>
        <p>
          When tenants in my building spoke at rallies, the landlord took them to court.
          That is not a coincidence and it is not a coincidence in your building either. Speaking
          out carries a real cost, and anyone who tells you otherwise has not done this.
        </p>
        <p>
          Retaliation against a tenant for organizing or asserting their rights is against the law
          in New York. But the law only helps you if you can <em>prove</em> the timeline. So write
          it down: what you did, what date, and what happened to you afterwards.
        </p>
        <p>
          And protect each other. Nobody should have to be the face of this alone. Spread the
          public-facing work across as many people as are willing, and never pressure anyone who
          isn't.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="warn">
      <span class="flag">The one that got us</span>
      <h3>Be extremely careful what you sign.</h3>
      <p>
        After our first rally, our landlord hired a major law firm. They demanded we sign a
        Memorandum of Understanding. The pitch: sign this, stop talking to the press, and we'll
        give you the building's confidential financial information.
      </p>
      <p>
        We signed. The financial information never came. Months later they terminated the MOU
        with no warning and no reason.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>The document was never about disclosure. It was about silence — and we gave it to
        them for free.</strong>
      </p>
      <p>
        Never sign anything without your lawyer reading it. Be especially suspicious of anything
        that limits what you can say publicly, and anything offered in exchange for information
        you haven't received yet. Your voice is the only leverage you have. Do not trade it for a
        promise.
      </p>
      <p style="font-size:15px;margin-top:16px;color:#7f1d1d">
        The one thing we got right: we insisted on writing TOPA language into that MOU. It nearly
        collapsed the talks. We insisted anyway. Insist.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="note" style="margin-top:36px">
      <b>Before any meeting with your landlord, an agency, or an elected official —</b>
      read <a href="/objections/" style="color:#78350f;font-weight:800">every objection, answered</a>.
      It's every argument they will make, with the response and the source. It also tells you
      honestly where they have a point, so you're not blindsided.
    </div>

    <h2 style="margin-top:56px">The countdown</h2>
    <p class="lead">Where you are in the clock changes what you should be doing.</p>

    <div class="clock">
      <div class="beat">
        <h4>Five or more years out</h4>
        <p>This is the golden window and almost nobody uses it. Form the association now, while there's no crisis to panic about. Establish the date. Build relationships with your elected officials before you need them. Identify preservation buyers. You will never have more leverage or more time than you have right now.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="beat">
        <h4>Three years out</h4>
        <p>Get a lawyer engaged. Make formal written contact with the landlord about their intentions. Start the conversation with the city and state housing agencies. Go public — build the campaign before you need it to save you.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="beat red">
        <h4>One year out</h4>
        <p>Full mobilization. Rallies, press, elected officials on the record. Your preservation buyer should be ready to make an offer. Expect the landlord to move fast, to obstruct, and to try to buy your silence. This is when the MOU shows up.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="beat red">
        <h4>After the expiration</h4>
        <p>It is not over. Good Cause may protect you. Other regulatory overlays may survive. A sale can still go to a preservation buyer. My building's credit expired and we are still here, still fighting, still organized. Expiration is a date, not a verdict.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="note" style="margin-top:44px">
      <b>This page is not legal advice, and I am not a lawyer.</b>
      I'm a tenant who has been through it and is still in it. Every situation is different, and
      the details of your building — what other subsidies it has, what your lease says, whether
      it's rent stabilized — change the answer enormously. Call one of the numbers above. They're
      free, and they know things I don't.
    </div>

  </div>
</main>

